I am at the federal courthouse, awaiting the sentencing of Solomon Dwek.
A shackled Solomon Dwek just entered the courtroom.
A shackled Solomon Dwek has entered the courtroom.
Judge says he is concerned about Dwek's activity while free on bail.
Prosecutor is outlining Dwek's cooperation with authorities.
Prosecutor says Dwek made about 2,600 recordings, resulting in 38 convictions.
Prosecutor says the 38 convictions would not have happened without Dwek; he calls the # "staggering."
Prosecutor says Dwek cooperated in both kidney trafficking and money laundering cases.
Kidney trafficking conviction was the most important of those attributed to Dwek, prosecutor says
#dwek Prosecutor calls kidney trafficking case "a unique and shocking criminal undertaking exposed by Mr. Dwek's cooperation."
#dwek Judge says kidney trafficking conviction was "very serious" and notes it was the first under the National Organ Transplant Act.
#dwek Dwek infiltrated criminal networks in the Hasidic community that laundered millions upon millions of dollars, prosecutor says.
#dwek Prosecutor: Dwek picked up bags of cash in NYC for Deal rabbi convicted of money laundering.
#dwek Tapes recorded by Dwek led to corruption conviction of Assemblyman Daniel Van Pelt, prosecutor says.
#dwek State: Dwek cooperation led to corruption convictions of Hoboken mayor and Jersey City politicians, among others.
#dwek Prosecutor: Dwek cooperated in Operation Bid Rig at great personal risk to himself.
#dwek Prosecutor: "Mr. Dwek's cooperation never waivered from the time he walked in the door in July of 2006."
#dwek Judge notes Dwek was facing a potential life sentence when he agreed to cooperate with authorities.
#dwek Prosecutor says that if given another year to investigate, Dwek's bank fraud may have grown from $50-100 million to $200 million.
#dwek Prosecutor tells judge Dwek's plea bargain is "not a sweetheart deal."
#dwek Dwek, handcuffed and in yellow jail uniform, takes copious notes during discourse between prosecutor and judge.
#dwek Judge says Dwek lied about stolen car charge, claimed to have never rented car that was returned late.
#dwek Judge: "He lies to the FBI for no apparent reason. What does that say about Mr. Dwek's personality?"
#dwek About the lie, prosecutor says Dwek panicked and fell back on old, bad habits.
#dwek Prosecutor calls lying "a character flaw that certainly applies to Mr. Dwek."
#dwek The lie landed Dwek in federal detention in Philadelphia, where he is known as "Dwek the rat," prosecutor says.
#dwek "Made members of organized crime were talking about him as a rat," prosecutor says of Dwek.
#dwek  10 minute recess underway in Dwek sentencing.
#dwek Defense attorney: "Mr. Dwek crossed the line. ...Greed got to him and power got to him."
#dwek Defense: Dwek was addicted to wheeling and dealing. He would go to a deal "like a drug addict needing a fix."
#dwek Defense says Dwek helped pay for funeral of young cancer victim and gave money to hospitals.
#dwek Defense: Had Dwek not ostracized himself from his community by helping feds,100s of people would have sent letters on his behalf.
#dwek Defense: Dwek thought he could get money to keep Ponzi scheme going, but was in over his head.
#dwek Dwek traded the respect of his community for the chance to get out of prison and see his kids.
#dwek Dwek addresses judge, apologizes to his victims.
#dwek Dwek breaks down, sniffling, during apology.
#dwek Dwek: "the balance of days on this earth I will live to make up to the people whom I've hurt so badly."
#dwek Dwek: "I wasn't brought up or raised to lie, to cheat, to steal or to defraud human beings.
#dwek Dwek tells judge his rabbi father lost his job because of his cooperation with Feds.
#dwek Dwek: "my father told me never to cooperate because it was against our religion and the Bible."
#dwek Dwek says his parents disowned him. "I have one person to blame, and that is myself."
#dwek Dwek says his community trusted him. "No one in my community ever wore a wire."
#dwek Dwek says one rabbi told him he had been laundering money for years.
#dwek Dwek: "I was lucky enough and made recordings at the direction of the FBI in NY, NJ, Pa. And Fla."
#dwek Dwek says that during first corruption trial he testified at, "criminal threats were made against my life."
#dwek Dwek says his family was relocated to Md. during first trial he testified at. "My kids were living in fear."
#dwek Dwek: "It was a very difficult time in our lives. I was under a lot of duress."
#dwek Dwek says his children have been senselessly persecuted and thrown out of school after school because of his cooperation with Feds.
#dwek Dwek: 9 y.o. son said to mother, "Are they going to come banging on the door & take you away like they took Daddy away?"
#dwek Dwek says after moving to Md., he was cursed at & chased out of pizzeria with his son when employees recognized him.
#dwek Dwek says his family has been persecuted "because I turned on my pen people."
#dwek Dwek: "I can 't go anywhere with my children, maybe forever, without fear, always looking over my children ."
#dwek Dwek to judge: If you give me another chance, I wll utilize that special gift.
#dwek Dwek thanks wife for coming to court to support him, and those who had courage to write letters on his behalf.
#dwek Dwek to judge: I'm a marked man. The chances of my dying a natural death are slim.
#dwek Dwek to judge: Thank you, your honor, for your time, your mercy, and your compassion.
#dwek They are taking another recess in the Dwek sentencing.
#dwek Judge sentences Dwek to 6 years in prison, bars him from future career in real estate and investment.
#dwek Dwek, standing hunched over, hangs head while judge imposes sentence.
#dwek Judge says Dwek's crimes were serious and brazen.
#dwek Judge says Dwek's crimes were not caused by bipolar disorder.
#dwek Judge says Dwek was an aggressive informant.
#dwek Judge on Dwek: I think his crimes are motivated by greed, not by his psychological condition.
#dwek Judge says Dwek's life of crime started at age 18, when he tried to bribe  a teacher.
#dwek Judge orders Dwek to pay $22.8 million in restitution to bank, in monthly installments of $300.
#dwek Defense attorney asks that Dwek be allowed to serve his sentence at federal prison in Cumberland, Md.
#dwek Dwek says something to wife and appears to be smiling as he is led out of the courtroom in handcuffs.
